- Very tight distribution (StdDev 1.49) → higher safe position sizing
- Avg Yearly Gain / Avg Drawdown ratio of **5.4** is excellent
- Short drawdown durations + high break-even probability = best
  psychological experience of all systems reviewed

---

### Cross-System Patterns and Insights

**On negative expectancy (System 3-3):**
- 90% win rate with W/L ratio of 0.10 = losing system
- Optimizer is useless: there is no position size that rescues
  a negative-expectancy system
- 2,968 trades needed for 95% chance of break-even (essentially never)

**On variance vs. expectancy tradeoffs:**
- System 3-5 (expectancy 4.10R, StdDev 15.84): 100% prob break-even,
  but only 10% win rate — requires extreme psychological tolerance
- System SQN3 (expectancy 0.45R, StdDev 1.49): 99.8% prob break-even,
  64% win rate — much smaller gains but far superior risk-adjusted metrics

**On optimal risk% range:**
- Across all positive-expectancy systems, **Opt. Retire** risk% ranges
  from **1.2% to 6.8%**
- Higher variance systems → lower optimal risk%
- Lower variance, higher-frequency systems → higher optimal risk%
- Max Return almost always produces **>80% ruin** — it is not a
  viable strategy in any of these systems

**On drawdown duration:**
- System 3-4: 83.2-month 95% drawdown duration (nearly 7 years)
- System SQN1: 31.4 months (~2.6 years)
- System SQN3: 3.6 months — the key differentiator for real-world
  tradability; most traders abandon systems during 2+ year drawdowns

**SQN series introduction:** The SQN systems (SQN1-SQN7) appear to
represent a progression of **System Quality Number** categories,
moving from poor to excellent systems to illustrate how SQN affects
optimal position sizing. The label format (SQN1 = lowest quality,
SQN7 = highest) suggests a structured comparison framework introduced
in a preceding chapter.

