## Appendix II: t-Scores

### Statistical Significance Testing

- **t-test**: Classical statistical test to determine if a sample differs from the population mean
- Formula: (difference between means / standard deviation of all scores) × √(number of scores)
- Purpose: Answer whether an **expectancy** (average R score) is significantly greater than zero

### System Quality Number and t-test

- When evaluating a trading system, the core question is: "Is the expectancy significantly greater than zero?"
- **System Quality Number** directly answers this via a t-test lookup table
- The test uses a **0.05 significance level**: any probability < 0.05 is considered significantly different from chance
- Anything with probability ≥ 0.05 could occur by random chance

### One-Tailed Test Approach

- Uses a **one-tailed test** (not two-tailed)
- Only tests if positive expectancy is significantly different from zero
- Ignores whether negative expectancy differs from zero (never want to trade negative expectancy systems)

### t-Score Reference Table

The table provided gives critical t-values for determining system significance:

- **Number of Trades**: 10–121+ (up to Infinite)
- **Significance Levels**: .25, .05, .025, .01
- Example: 100 trades with System Quality Number of 1.85
  - At .05 level: critical value is 1.645
  - 1.85 > 1.645 = significant at the 0.05 level
  - System has < 5% chance of occurring by random chance

### Practical Application

- If System Quality Number exceeds the critical value at your chosen significance level, the system's positive expectancy is real
- The 0.05 level is recommended as standard for trading system evaluation
- More trades improve statistical reliability and lower critical thresholds

<!-- pp. 381-399 -->

## Glossary

### Core Position Sizing Concepts

- **algorithm** — a rule or set of rules for computing; a procedure for calculating a mathematical function
- **anti-martingale strategy** — increase position size when winning, decrease when losing (opposite of martingale)
- **martingale strategy** — increase position size after losses; classic version doubles bet size after each loss
- **asset allocation** — how professionals decide to allocate capital; Tharp argues its real power is determining *how much* to invest in each class — i.e., it's another term for position sizing
- **position sizing** — coined by Tharp in *Trade Your Way to Financial Freedom*; the most important of six key elements of successful trading; determines how large a position will be throughout the course of a trade; based on current equity
- **fixed ratio position sizing** — position sizing altered to some ratio of the account (called **delta**) rather than a percentage
- **generalized ratio position sizing (GRPS)** — adjusts the speed at which position sizing increases with FRPS
- **percent risk model** — position sizing determined by limiting risk on each position to a certain percentage of equity
- **percent volatility model** — position sizing determined by limiting volatility (usually defined by **ATR**) to a certain percentage of equity
- **percent margin model** — position sizing based on the margin set by the exchange
- **equal units model** — purchase an equal dollar amount of each position
- **units per fixed amount of money model** — buy one unit per X dollars in account (e.g., one contract per $25,000)
- **multiple-tier position sizing** — change position sizing variable multiple times as performance criteria are met
- **two-tier position sizing** — starts at one level, moves to another when predetermined criteria are met
- **market's money** — core equity sized conservatively; profits (market's money) sized more aggressively
- **optimal f** — method developed by **Ralph Vince**; depends on worst-case loss to date; uses iteration to determine position sizing
- **scaling-in** — adding to position size based on predetermined criteria until reaching a maximum level
- **scaling-out** — reducing size when open risk or open volatility exceeds a predetermined level; maintains constant risk/volatility

### Equity Models

- **total equity** — value of account = cash + total value of all open positions
- **core equity** — subtract the allocation of each position (assume it's gone until closed); base position sizing for new trades on what remains
- **reduced total equity** — subtract allocations for new positions, but add back amounts saved by raising stops; middle ground between total and core equity
- **equity crossover** — position sizing changes based on equity moving above or below some average
- **equity curve** — value of your account over time, illustrated graphically

### Risk & Performance Metrics

- **R-multiple** — all profits/losses expressed as multiples of initial risk (R); a $100 profit on $10 initial risk = 10R; any system can be described by its R-multiple distribution
- **R-value** — the initial risk taken in a given position, as defined by initial stop loss
- **initial risk** — difference between stop level and entry price; referred to as R throughout the book
- **expectancy** — mean R of an R-multiple distribution; how much you can expect to make per dollar risked over many trades
- **expectunity** — expectancy × opportunity; e.g., 0.6R expectancy × 100 trades/year = 60R expectunity
- **positive expectancy** — system will make money long-term if played at sufficiently low risk; mean of R-multiple distribution is positive
- **negative expectancy system** — will never make money long-term; all casino games are designed this way; also includes high-reliability systems with occasional large losses
- **system quality number (SQN)** — based on statistical t-score; determines system quality AND serves as basis for position sizing to meet objectives
- **hit rate** — percentage of winners; also called *reliability of your system*
- **win rate** — percentage of closed trades in which you make money
- **reward-to-risk ratio** — average annual return divided by maximum peak-to-trough drawdown; over 3.0 = excellent; also can mean average winner divided by average loser
- **Sharpe ratio** — developed by Nobel Laureate **William F. Sharpe**; (return − risk-free rate) ÷ standard deviation of returns; measures risk-adjusted performance
- **maximum adverse excursion (MAE)** — maximum loss attributable to price movement against a position during the life of a trade
- **peak-to-trough drawdown** — maximum drawdown from highest equity peak to lowest trough prior to new equity high
- **drawdown** — decrease in account value from losing trades or paper losses on open positions

### Objectives & Goals

- **objectives** — what you wish to accomplish as a trader; can be stated as desired goal, worst-case drawdown to avoid, or combination; purpose of position sizing is to help meet objectives
- **retire** — the trading goal amount (the "retire amount")
- **optimal retire** — position sizing percentage giving largest probability of reaching stated goal
- **retire-less-ruin** — probability of reaching goal minus probability of having worst-case drawdown
- **ruin** — amount of drawdown at which you would stop trading
- **optimal position size** — best position sizing method to achieve your objectives
- **optimal target risk percentage** — optimal portfolio heat ÷ number of trades likely to have open simultaneously
- **portfolio heat** — total open risk in portfolio at any given time; generally should not exceed 20%
- **open risk** — difference between current price and stop value for all open positions; another term for portfolio heat

### Trading System Elements

- **system** — complete system has: (1) setup conditions, (2) entry signal, (3) worst-case disaster stop, (4) profit-taking exit, (5) position sizing algorithm
- **entry** — part of system that signals how/when to enter the market
- **exit** — part of system that tells how/when to exit
- **trailing stop** — stop-loss order that moves with the prevailing trend; only moved when market goes in your favor; never moved in opposite direction
- **disaster stop** — stop-loss order to determine worst-case loss in a position
- **backtesting** — testing a trading strategy on prior time periods; most technical analysis strategies tested this way
- **optimize** — find parameters/indicators that best predict price changes in historical data; warning: "a highly optimized system usually does a poor job of predicting future prices"
- **postdictive error** — error made by incorporating future data you shouldn't know; e.g., buying on open knowing the close is up
- **mechanical trading** — all actions determined by computer with no additional human decision making
- **discretionary trading** — depends on trader instincts; best discretionary traders develop a systematic approach then use discretion in exits and position sizing

### Market & Price Concepts

- **average true range (ATR)** — average over last X days of the true range: largest of (1) today's high–low, (2) today's high–yesterday's close, (3) today's low–yesterday's close
- **volatility** — range of prices in a given time period; one of the most useful concepts in trading
- **six market types** — up-quiet, up-volatile, sideways-quiet, sideways-volatile, down-quiet, down-volatile
- **group heat** — total open risk in any one sector or commodity grouping; important to control correlated positions
- **consolidation** — pause in market where prices move in limited range and don't trend (also: congestive range)
- **breakout** — move up or down from a consolidation or band of sideways movement
- **gap** — area on price chart with no trades; typically between one day's close and next day's open
- **support** — price level a stock has historically had difficulty falling below; area where buyers come in
- **resistance** — area on chart a stock can trade up to but cannot seem to exceed for a period
- **limit move** — price change reaching the exchange's limit; trading halted when reached
- **slippage** — difference between expected entry price and actual fill price
- **marked to market** — open positions credited/debited based on closing price each day

### Psychological & Bias Terms

- **gambler's fallacy** — belief that a loss is due after a string of winners, or a gain after a string of losers
- **judgmental heuristics** — mental shortcuts for quick decision making; lead to biases that often cause money losses
- **psychological loss** — loss resulting from natural biases and psychology; usually larger than 1R
- **holy grail system** — mythical system that always works with zero drawdowns; doesn't exist; "the real meaning of the Holy Grail is right on track: it suggests that the secret is inside you"
- **best-case example** — when books illustrate points with charts that appear to perfectly predict the market; most examples are not nearly as good as the selected one
- **prediction** — great traders make money by "cutting losses short and letting profits run," which has nothing to do with prediction
- **lotto bias** — (see asset allocation entry) tendency to think of asset allocation as picking which asset class vs. how much to invest

### Key Figures Referenced in Index

- **Ralph Vince** — optimal f developer; Mathematics of Gambling
- **Ryan Jones** — fixed ratio position sizing; dampening factor concept
- **Jack Schwager** — Market Wizards, New Market Wizards
- **William Eckhardt** — featured in New Market Wizards
- **Curtis Faith** — Way of the Turtle; one of the original Turtles
- **Ed Seykota** — Secrets of the Masters Trading Game
- **Daniel Kahneman** — Prospect Theory; judgmental heuristics
- **Amos Tversky** — behavioral biases research
- **Larry Williams** — position sizing and percent risk work
